Matt Blaze (mab@research.att.com) wrote:
: of the keyspace, etc), the concept of "most secure" goes well beyond
: the underlying cipher.  Things like PGP encrypt individual files (and,
: I assume, data streams) on demand, while things like Diskreet present
: a file system interface that includes encryption as a basic feature.

I agree that the definition of 'secure' is subject to varying scope.
But just evaluating encryption systems within their claimed scope,
PGP is still the most secure.

But this does not contradict the fact that if a user requires invisible
whole file system security, then PGP is insecure for them.

